{
  "doc_id": "14433",
  "text": "Hedonism and utilitarianism are not necessarily two ends of a one-dimensional scale [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . A product may be high and low on both hedonic and utilitarian attributes [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , though its aggregate perception could be singularly hedonic or utilitarian [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] and, compared to utilitarian consumption, hedonic consumption is thought of as more discretionary [CITATION_7] . For instance, a pair of shoes can appeal to a consumer for both its functional features (e.g., durability) as well as its hedonic features (e.g., looks). Thus, in line with [CITATION_8] we recognize that both usage and consumption goals determine whether a product is perceived as primarily hedonic or utilitarian.",
